<br>
I would personally pick the &quot;Ignore it, and leave if she persists&quot; option. Why? Because of a couple of different reasons. <br>
<br>
This is a game, and you have no damn right bringing up your personal problems with me. In fact, the reason why I started thinking about this is that someone threw the &quot;My husband beat me up last night&quot; line at a friend of mine some time back, and he was incredolous. &quot;I don't wanna know about it!&quot; he said, both angry and laughing at the same time -- &quot;what a bunch of losers and headcases there are in this game!&quot; and I fully agree. Now, there's one thing to ask for advice about the game, game related stuff like computer equipment, or say, someone's travelling to Ireland, and there's an Irish player, go fer it, sure, fine. <br>
<br>
Secondly, the last goddamn thing in the world you wanna do, is get involved in shit like that. As we all know, there are some real fruitloops out there, who'll make crazy shit like this up, to get pity and sympathy and attention. But even if the tales are true, hell, it's even worse -- you end up saying &quot;Your husband is an asshole&quot; and a week later, they've made up and you get the husband sending you a tell saying &quot;So, I hear you think I'm an asshole...&quot; I don't know if we have any cops reading this board, but I've heard that domestic disputes is a situation cops really do not like... I can believe it. I had some neighbors that went nuts all the time, you'd have the wife screaming HEEEEELP!! struggling, wrestling out on the porch, with her husband who tried to shut her up and drag her back into the appartment, ten minutes later the cops are on their door, and she's answering, going &quot;Domestic dispute, that musta been a crank call, how DARE you insinuate that!?&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uiniyeni.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Iniyeni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/13/01 5:10:42 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> I'm with you, Cogs, for similar reasons. It's hard for me to be unsympathetic to such a claim even so, my mother is a domestic violence counselor and my sister was in an abusive marriage for a couple years. It's a horrible situation, but there are two things to remember.<br>
<br>
One, you can't help the person by giving advice. Period. They can only help themselves. They will leave when they are ready to and not before, even when they are terrified and know they should get out. All you can do to help a woman who is being abused is to say &quot;When you're ready to leave, I will support your decision, here are some women's shelters you can call.&quot; If you offer help of any other kind (money, a place to stay, etc.) you open yourself up to a lot of legal and physical trouble, and verbal advice is a waste of time because the woman already KNOWS she should leave at the point where she's even willing to admit the abuse occurs. <br>
<br>
Two, there are a lot of wackos out there. I personally have encountered people who've spent years crafting an elaborate lie to hide RL gender, looks, marital status, etc. I used to staff on an online RP site where one of the site founders &quot;died&quot; due to complications from diabetes and &quot;her&quot; supposed lesbian partner came on to thank the site players for the outpouring of supportive emails, etc. after this &quot;death.&quot; A few months later this person turned up on the site again as a different identity, and as we discovered, &quot;she&quot; was in fact a middle-aged male plumber from Brooklyn who killed off the online persona because he couldn't think of any other way out of the web of lies. Lies his RL wife aided and abetted for over two years, including pretending to be &quot;her&quot; on the phone. Never ever believe anyone's sob story online until you have proof in the form of court documents, I say. And even then be wary.  <p>Einthe MacBuff<BR>Diamond Katana<BR>Shaman of the Tribunal<BR>"Irish Diplomacy: The ability to tell someone to go to Hell in such a way that they look forward to the trip."</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uiniyeni.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Iniyeni</A> at: 6/13/01 5:11:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uaerroch.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aerroch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/13/01 7:00:32 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> I picked the &quot;Ignore it, and leave if she persists&quot; option as well.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I have a heart of gold the size of Texas, and if a friend of mine in real life was ever being beaten, I would go over and make sure the guy never ever thought about so much as farting in a woman's direction again (yes, this is macho toughguy stuff that just sounds nice to say, but it is truly the way i feel).  But in a computer game, where I come to relax and have fun, and where I don't know any of the people in real life, don't bring those sorts of problems to me.  If you're looking for sympathy, call your friends and family.  If you're looking for help with the situation, call the police.  That's what each of those respective groups are there for.  EQ is not the place to be looking for a pity party, nor is it a place to go and expect help with a serious situation such as abuse.  There are shelters for that sort of thing.<br>
<br>
If I come across as cold, then so be it, but a distinction needs to be made between the two areas, and separation needs to be kept.  Especially if I don't know the person all that well. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uaerroch.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aerroch</A> at: 6/13/01 7:04:13 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uiniyeni.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Iniyeni</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/13/01 8:31:04 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> Aerroch:<br>
<br>
You sound like my kind of guy, at least in your impulses. But keep in mind one thing about domestic abuse, just in case you ever do run into this situation in your RL. If you go threaten the abusive husband, you'd better kill him and make damn sure the cops never find out who did it, because otherwise the second you leave he'll take it all out on her. It's a classic pattern, in fact frequently these kinds of actions by loved ones of the abusee will cause the abuser to become *more* violent, sometimes even killing the woman. <br>
<br>
Sorry to interject such a serious note here, but I've seen the case files. <p>Einthe MacBuff<BR>Diamond Katana<BR>Shaman of the Tribunal<BR>"Irish Diplomacy: The ability to tell someone to go to Hell in such a way that they look forward to the trip."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/utrindletrueheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trindle Trueheart</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/14/01 7:22:56 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> Well... i picked the comfort/advice option...<br>
<br>
Why?  I just can't turn my back on people.. i'd rather be dragged down with the problem then know in my heart that i turned my back to someone.<br>
<br>
This is a Game... i do not log on to play counselor.. but i do end up hearing lots of things about people's RL problems and such.  <br>
<br>
A woman is being beaten..<br>
That means one thing for sure.  Her husband is a controller... and she could very possibly be confined to her house.  No, i don't mean tied down and confined.  I mean emotionally battered to the point of not having the guts to walk out her front door to the real world.  In cases of violent relationships, the person being hurt usually thinks they are getting hurt because of it being their fault... it's all messed up.  But anyways...<br>
<br>
i believe you should offer advice.  That advice being, get the hell out of there.  If you can, send me an e-mail and let me know you're okay,  after you leave.  <br>
<br>
If she won't take the advice, there's really nothing else you can do.  DON'T feed her with sympathy... because sometimes that's what people are fishing for.. that and just plain old attention.  Sick but true.<br>
