</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ucogito.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cogito</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of the Whacky Woondarland</span><br>  Posts: 430<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/26/01 8:50:33 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://server49.hypermart.net/voxton/flash/mouse.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> Hmmm, the majority of people picked the &quot;help&quot; option. <br>
<br>
I would like to see a few more people explain their reasoning for this decision. Quite a few people voiced their opinion, but not many have explained why. I'm not out to prove anyone wrong -- I'm not really sure there is a right or wrong here. But as interesting as I think this whole cyber-world interaction is, I still think there are things that belong in the real world, and this -- as well as intimate relationships are some of them. <br>
<br>
An emergency that I heard about years ago, was a woman who lived alone, having a medical emergency of some sorts, and managed to get help via whatever game or chat system she was on -- that makes sense. Emergency, or whatnot. This may have been an urban legend of course -- I think I heard about this happening over CB radio or someting like that too. But an emergency, I can understand that. That's different. <br>
<br>
The only time that I can remember having tried to help/listen, is when someone that I knew played another character, and had started a new one, which he called stupid, or idiot, or something along those lines. I said hahah, good name, and he replied well, I must be, cos my dad says so. Now, that pisses me off a helluva lot more than a wife beater. I've no kids of my own, but I've worked with kids a few years, so I tried to help. Dunno what good it did. But a kid is a kid -- they don't have any options, as far as going somewhere. In a battered wife's mind there aren't any options either really, but kids are different. Not that I'd say it's ok to meddle with that either of course, that's just the only time I remember getting into it. <br>
<br>
If people need help, they should get it in real life. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ullanowarelf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llanowar Elf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/27/01 5:20:51 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> I for one, chose the "try and help" option.  But by choosing the "try and help" option...all I really meant was "not shrug them off and tell them this isn't the proper medium for them to be bringing this up".<br>
<br>
I'm not saying you should offer advice, tell them "things will get better", or try and fix the situation in any way.  You're probably not qualified to do that, and you may end up misleading an already confused individual.  What I do say you should do is listen (this is, of course, assuming you want to help), and maybe provide a bit of sympathy.<br>
<br>
Hell...I think a lot of the people out there who do this only really want to feel like someone out there cares about their situation, so why not let them indulge?  They could be talking to an NPC programmed with the ELIZA logic and it would probably work as well, but the fact that they BELIEVE there's a real-live person at the other end makes them feel better.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is, if someone brings something up like this, they obviously want to talk about it...otherwise they wouldn't have brought it up.  Assuming they want to talk about it, I'm usually willing to have a couple extra purple lines going across my screen if it in some way makes someone feel good...<br>
<br>
Llano <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/upinerenforestheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pineren Forestheart</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Surprise, Surprise, Surprise!</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/27/01 6:43:52 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> I would choose to comfort her.  Why? Because i can't let a problem go that is that is like this.  Obviously the husband is controlling, thats how most of them turn out to be if they hit women.  I would tell her to get help, call someone who cares about her, then let things roll.  It all depends on the situation.  if she was afraid to leave the house then call a friend or mother and they will probably do something about it. But then when she is out of that situation of the husband i would tell her to find help.  bout it.  Bye <p>QuAcK!  I'm A dOnKeY!</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ubowynn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bowynn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Head Whore of Playsure Palace</span><br>  Posts: 408<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/27/01 9:06:43 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.visveres.com/sigs/bowynnsm.jpg width=169 hieght=175></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Serious Question -- what would you do?</span><hr size=1> Llanowar made a very good point...<br>
<br>
Do you even comprehend what a lift it can be to imagine someone gives a shit about you, when you're feeling down and out?  They don't know you, but fact is, it's another human being who may be severely lacking in self esteem or confidence.<br>
<br>
Just a couple minutes of your time to someone who really just needs a kind word... isn't that a reward in itself?  Jesus, do you know what kind of power that is?   I forget who said it, but &quot;Make them love you and they will die for you&quot; is all too true.<br>
<br>
NOW, I'm not saying be nice to manipulate people.  What I'm saying is to realize it's an awesome power that you possess in a world that you are largely powerless in.<br>
<br>
I had a little Rogue send me a tell asking if my guild had a minimum level to join.  I replied yes, lvl 50, to which he repleid with &quot;sigh.&quot;<br>
<br>
I asked him what was wrong.  Then I did a who on him - lvl 14 if I remember right.  He says back &quot;nothing, just seems like I'm not getting anywhere.. thinking of quitting.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, I've been there.  Sounds like this person needs a little boost.  So I says &quot;look, man, the lower level game is the most fun you're ever going to have.  This is where you make the friends who will stick with you, regardless of guild.  This is where you make your memories.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah, but I just don't think.. I dunno... are rogues supposed to suck?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;HAHAH.. dude, wait till some of the higher levels where people will BEG you to join thier groups... some dungeons can't even be practically done without a Rogue..&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;really?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah, and I tell you something else.. keep at it and if I get any Rogue drops the guild doesn't need I'll look you up and give you a present, how's that sound?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;WOW, thanks!!!  You serious?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;yep.. writing your name down&quot;<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Okay, not exactly an out of game moment, but all the same he sounded down in RL and I had the ability to perk him up a bit.. so I did.  <br>
<br>
On a very different note, a while ago a person who I won't name, was really freaking me out and acting odd.  I finally told her she needed to tell me what the fuck is going on or I was logging... nothing for a good 5 minutes.  I said &quot;Fine, logging off&quot; and she sent me a tell &quot;wait..&quot;  I said &quot;What?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You wanna know what's wrong?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I DID ask...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Fine.  Two nights ago I was raped.&quot;<br>
<br>
You think it was easy for me to even respond?  Do you think me not knowing her in RL made it any less shocking?  Do you think I considered her LESS deserving of my attention or care?<br>
<br>
No, no, and no.  We talked for hours.  She cried, got hysterical, went silent, talked some more... and in the end she went to sleep.  Now, almost a year later she has a boyfriend and should be having a baby in about 5 months.  She seems very happy.  I found out much later that she was intending to kill herself that night.  Did I change that?  Probably not, but if there is even the REMOTEST chance that *I* had ANYTHING to do with her changing her course.. well, wasn't that worth some of my time? <p><center>
